pr_review_body:
@lobsiger thanks a lot for adding this feature, it is very nice results you get!
I have just started with the review, but maybe we can start with that?
There is a lot of places which are flagged as not tested indeed. I understand that Xarray can be a bit frightening, how about starting with tests using regular numpy arrays first, that we can then adapt to Xarray?

@t0yv0 the motivating document checks out, and not much to review except that out matrix of [linux, mac, windows] and [ARM, x86-64] lines up, I'm unfamiliar with this go wrapping business but it makes sense to me as well.

Only nit would be that if there's an issue to review or clean up the CI process, we add this business to it and if not we create one. 

From experience, CI cleanup is always a $(currentQuarter+1) task, but I think @Frassle & you are on the right track thinking about overhauling it and this just adds to the evidence pile for making time for it.

@gshuflin already added support for the return types of rules to indicate that they are failures, and thus uncacheable. It's used for one thing right now: marking processes with non-zero exit codes uncacheable. https://github.com/pantsbuild/pants/blob/9501b3c456b8be6557c919aac44c691703a07d15/src/rust/engine/src/nodes.rs#L1383-L1399

This change should probably use that facility + a flag on the engine-aware return type that indicates that the result was a failure.

The actual mechanism here is small, so I'm fine with landing this temporarily though. Would be good to follow up to use the existing mechanism, which will be less error prone for further error types.

/LGTM

@zw0610 Thanks for the PR!

/cc @kuikuikuizzZ

The body of both functions is very much the same, the only difference is one calls to `git_merge_base_many` and the other one calls to `git_merge_base_octopus`.

Instead please write a static function, so there's not duplicated code. Then it may look something like:

```c
typedef int (*git_merge_base_xxx_t)(git_oid *out, git_repository *repo, size_t length, const git_oid input_array[]);

static PyObject *
merge_base_xxx(Repository *self, PyObject *args, git_merge_base_xxx_t git_merge_base_xxx)
{
   [...]
}

PyObject *
Repository_merge_base_octopus(Repository *self, PyObject *args)
{
    return merge_base_xxx(self, args, &git_merge_base_octopus);
}
```

@bklebel could you please remove methods `check_errors` since, for SCPI instruments, is provided by `Instrument` class ?
I would replace also `super(Keithley2000, self)` with 'super()'
For the rest, it looks good to me.
